document_data.History:
Solon was was founded in {{Yearlink|-6422}} as the capital city of [[Imaskar#Middle Kingdoms Period|Lower Imaskar]]. It would continue to be such throughout the Middle Kingdoms period of the empire. It was once famous for its iron mines.{{cite book/Blood Charge|61}}

After the fall of Imaskar, the ancient city of Solon sought to carve itself a new empire from the desert wastes. It succeeded for a time, gaining control of most of the land south of the Raurin Alta. It traded with [[Ra-Khati]] and [[Durpar]]. Slowly, however, as the desert spread further, [[Mulhorand]] took [[Brightstar Lake|Gbor Nor]], and [[Shou]] conquerors cut Solon's ties with the lands to the north, Solon lost its grip on its territories. The city temporarily became a part of the Shou empire at some point during the Kao dynasty.{{cite book/Blood Charge|55}} After a succession of weak kings over a period of centuries, Solon was only left with the city itself.

A lich by the name of [[Ambuchar Devayam]] took power as raja of the city sometime around {{yearlink|1310}}. {{cite book/Storm Riders|32}} Per a book from the city of Ra-Khati, he attempted to conquer [[Ra-Khati]] shortly after, with the help of [[Gaumahavi]]; he ultimately failed despite coming close.{{cite book/Storm Riders|11}} Later sources state Ambuchar took the city at the head of an army from [[Durpar]], sometime after the eruption of {{yearlink|1360}}.{{cite book/Blood Charge|58}}

The nearby volcano had erupted at least twice since the initial foundation of the city, leading to two rebuildings.{{cite book/Blood Charge|64}} had been raised atop the remains. At least one of the mummies in the city was 2000 years old at that time, give or take 10 years, which would place its raising around the year {{yearlink|-640}}. Solon had been in Kao control starting from some point after {{yearlink|-225}}, when that dynasty took control, and before the {{yearlinkName|-150}}, as said control predated the fall of [[Narfell]] and [[Raumathar]].{{cite book/The Horde/Volume I|19}}

On {{yearlink|1360}}, Ambuchar enslaved most of the population of the city and had them excavate in search of Imaskari artifacts, cutting off all trade. He turned the dead into zombies so they would continue to work after their lives were exhausted. The lich continued these activities throughout the year, until adventurers using four ebony artifacts from [[Imaskar]] broke the spell he used to rejuvenate his phylactery. The broken enchantment caused a great volcanic eruption about twenty minutes later, burying the entire city under ash and magma.{{cite book/Blood Charge|64}} Some sources blamed the eruption on the Raja's mishandling of an artifact instead.

Survivors from the eruption related that the Raja had unearthed a temple to the Paraelemental power of Ice, and the Quasielemental powers of Ash and Vacuum. The temple itself had survived, encased in a hollow sphere of black stone after the eruption.

Imaskari Level Landmarks.Ebony Temple:
The Ebony Temple was actually visible from the Great Pit, as the monolith on its center was actually its tip. It had a square base at the center of the Inner Temple. On each corner of the temple, a building with a diamond-shaped base protected one scroll each; an infrared-beam trap would fill the room with a ''[[fireball]]'' if anyone triggered it.

The temple's central courtyard held four ponds in the shape of a flower with four petals. Each of these ponds transported the person in question to a location in a different plane, yet held entirely in rooms within the Ebony Temple; one ebony artifact was held within each of those rooms.{{cite book/Blood Charge|62-64}}

The Main chamber of the temple held the ''bottomless pit of fire'', which was full of bubbling lava and connected in fact to an underground chamber full of the same. It was the source of the lava for the {{yearlink|1360}} eruption, after four ebony artifacts were cast into it.{{cite book/Blood Charge|62-64}}
